5. **`module-file-scoped-imports` — RED-SEEDED, fix NOT landed (needs attended verify).**
   Divergence CONFIRMED vs spec + cue v0.16.1 (three faces: same-name-different-target,
   shadow-leak, sibling-not-visible). Seeds committed `.known-red` under
   `testdata/modules/file_scoped_import_{collision,shadow}` + green over-scope guard `…_share`;
   module gate gained `.known-red` quarantine so they stay committed without breaking green.
   - *Why it needs a human:* the fix is core resolve/eval surgery. Refs are resolved to
     positional de-Bruijn `refId`s in ONE `resolveStructRefs` pass over the post-`meet` merged
     struct (`Runtime.lean:22`); imports are prepended to the single shared depth-0 frame
     (`Module.bindImports`/`loadPackage`, `Module.lean:153,536`). Per-file scoping fights the
     positional model — `meet` re-layouts the field frame, and imports need a per-file frame
     while package FIELDS stay shared (cross-file bare refs must still resolve; guard `…_share`
     pins this). A subtle wrongness here silently corrupts cert-manager/argocd — exactly the
     L5 "pins have been wrong" trap. Out of AFK envelope.
   - *What I'd do (recommended, so a one-word go unblocks):* give each file's imports UNIQUE
     synthetic importBinding labels (e.g. `\x00imp\x00<fileIdx>\x00<name>`, uncollidable with
     user idents), prepend ALL files' uniquely-labelled bindings to the merged struct (distinct
     slots → no same-label `meet`-to-bottom, so drop `dedupeBindings`; same package in N files
     → N slots, referenced separately, never met). Then per file, BEFORE merge, walk the body
     and rewrite `.ref name` → `.ref <uniqueLabel(file,name)>` ONLY when `name` is one of THAT
     file's imports AND not shadowed by an enclosing binder (field/let/for/alias); leave every
     other ref untouched. Existing post-merge `resolveStructRefs` then maps unique labels to
     their slots. This PRESERVES import SHARING (one slot per file-import, refId-referenced —
     no perf blowup) — do NOT substitute the package VALUE at each ref site (clean but copies a
     big package per reference → cert-manager perf trap). The one correctness risk is the
     shadow-detection walk matching cue's scoping EXACTLY; reuse the frame-pushing shape of
     `resolveValueWithFuel` (`Resolve.lean`) so shadowing can't drift, and verify against cue
     across: nested `let x`, `for x in`, top-level field `x`, value alias `x=`, and the three
     seed faces. When it lands: delete the two `.known-red` markers (the gate then enforces
     them) and pin face-3 (sibling-not-visible error) too.
